The coordinates of the vertices of the polygon are given as: 1. \((0,1 - \sqrt{3})\) 2. \((1,1 - \sqrt{3})\) 3. \((3 - \sqrt{3}, \sqrt{3} - 2)\) 4. \((\sqrt{3}, 0)\) 5. \((\sqrt{3}, 1)\) 6. \((3 - \sqrt{3}, 3 - \sqrt{3})\) 7. \((1, \sqrt{3})\) 8. \((0, \sqrt{3})\) 9. \((\sqrt{3} - 2, 3 - \sqrt{3})\) 10. \((1 - \sqrt{3}, 1)\) 11. \((1 - \sqrt{3}, 0)\) 12. \((\sqrt{3} - 2, \sqrt{3} - 2)\) Using the shoelace formula, we calculate the area by summing the terms \(x_i y_{i+1} - x_{i+1} y_i\) for each vertex and taking half the absolute value. After detailed calculations, the total sum of these terms is found to be \(-46 + 32\sqrt{3}\). Taking half of the absolute value gives the area as \(16\sqrt{3} - 23\). The area is expressed in the form \(m\sqrt{n} + p\) where \(m = 16\), \(n = 3\), and \(p = -23\). The absolute value of \(m + n + p\) is \(|16 + 3 - 23| = 4\). Thus, the final answer is \(\boxed{4}\).
